[normal]Written evidence from Thompsons Solicitors (CMI0029)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1. [bold]Executive Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Our submission focuses on four issues: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our central point is that the 
[normal]public is being poorly serv
[normal]ed 
[normal]by the 
[normal]car 
[normal]insurance industry.
[normal] Our submission 
[normal]produces evidence
[normal] that the major car insurers have used their strong position 
[normal]in 
[normal]one of only two 
[normal]legally-required 
[normal]insurance markets in the UK 
[normal]to boost their profits and returns to 
[normal]their 
[normal]shareholders at the e
[normal]xpense of consumers and access to justice. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]S
[normal]ome 
[normal]car insurers 
[normal]are now admitting they over-
[normal]stated the problem of 
[normal]personal 
[normal]bodily injury
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]are 
[normal]releas
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]hundreds of 
[normal]millions 
[normal]pounds from their
[normal] reserves 
[normal]in the form of 
[normal]huge pay outs to shareholders.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The letter 
[normal](
[normal]29.10.13
[normal]) 
[normal]from the Transport Select Committee chair, Louise 
[normal]Ellman
[normal] MP, to the Secretary of State for Justice, Chris Grayling MP, asks the government to explain 
[normal]how
[normal] it will monitor whether or not insurers will honour their commitment to ensure t
[normal]hat any cost reductions resulting from legal reforms are passed through to consumers.
[normal] In the absence of proper regulation of this broken market
[normal],
[normal] we
[normal] 
[normal]believe motorists will not gain any benefit from a reduction in the number of accidents and claims
[normal].
[normal] Car insu
[normal]rers should operate transparently and should not seek to influence public policy using information that cannot be independently verified.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The lack of transparency on the part of the leading car insurers is most clearly evident in the failure of AVIVA and [bold]AXA to provide information on the profits they make from this captive market.  We believe that their failure to report trading figures for car insurance is a clear breach of International Financial Reporting Standards, which require public companies to rep[bold]ort separately on an operating segment contributing 10% or more to overall reported profit.[bold] We urge the Transport Select Committee to seek an explanation for [bold]their failure to comply with this[bold] basic reporting requirement.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]As a 
[normal]short-term
[normal] measure
[normal], we argue 
[normal]that the car insurers should share some of their inflated profits with the public through a windfall tax that would be ring-fenced for investment in measures to improve road safety. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This submission consists mainly of new information that has emerged sinc
[normal]e the 
[normal]T
[normal]ransport Select Committee’s consultation 
[normal]in April 2013
[normal], to which we also made a submission
[normal], a copy of which is attached.
[normal] The arguments we put forward in that submission still stand. The information that has emerged subsequently serves only to reinfo
[normal]rce them.
