[normal]3.2[bold] Profits - substantial and rising[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Direct Line[bold] - In the first nine
[normal] months of 2013, Direct Line made an operating profit of £418m, a 20.1% increase on the same period last year (£348m). In its annual accounts, Direct Line gives a separate figure for operating profit from 
[normal]UK
[normal] motor insurance. In 2012, this was £262m, a 3% i
[normal]ncrease on 2011 (£255m).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Admiral[bold] - 
[normal]In the first half of 2013, the second largest car insurer saw its profits from the UK market increase 5% to £192.7 million (H1 2012: £183.3 million). This follows a bumper year in 2012 when its profit from the UK car 
[normal]ins
[normal]urance
[normal] rose 19% to £373m (2011: £314m).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]AVIVA[bold] - The third largest car insurer does not divulge its profits from selling motor insurance, despite - like Direct Line and Admiral - being listed on the London Stock Exchange
[normal]. Its 2012 annual report did, howeve
[normal]r, say that
[normal] 
[normal]it had increased the number of motor insurance policies sold by 250,000 to nearly 2.5 
[normal]million 
[normal]customers. It also said 
[normal]the group had generated £448m in operating profit from selling general insurance in the UK, which included ‘
[normal]good profitability
[normal] in personal lines’ 
[normal](
[normal]motor
[normal] and homeowner
[normal] insurance
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]International Financial Reporting Standards 
[normal](IFRS) 
[normal]require public companies to report
[normal] 
[normal]separately on an operating segment that contributes 10% or more to overall reported profit. 
[normal]Given that 
[normal]AVIVA 
[normal]achiev
[normal]ed a better ‘combined operating ratio’ for motor insurance than Direct Line (97% versus 101.6%) – albeit on a smaller customer base – it seems very likely that UK motor insurance on its own accounted for more than 10% of AVIVA’s 2012 operating profit of £1
[normal].888 billion. On this basis
[normal], we would argue AVIVA is in breach of IFRS 
[normal]segmental reporting requirements.
[normal] Indeed, once non-operating and restructuring costs are added back, 
[normal]AVIVA made a profit before tax of only £25m, which suggests profits from motor insur
[normal]ance
[normal] 
[normal]have been propping up an ailing company and funding mouth-watering pay outs to shareholders (see below) and executives (including a £5m plus remuneration package for new chief executive Mark Wilson).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]AXA[bold] - The French-headquartered insurance group, wh
[normal]ich is listed on the Paris Bourse, does not give separate profit figures for UK motor insurance. However, AXA UK &amp; Ireland did issue a press release on 21
[normal]st
[normal] February 2013 saying: “Motor profitability improved in 2012
[normal].”
[normal] 
[normal]As with AVIVA, we would argue AXA is 
[normal]in breach of IFRS and should be required to provide segmental trading information for this market.
[normal]&#xa0;
