[normal]3.5[bold] Having it both ways[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Vehicle repair referral f[bold]ees[bold] - The 
[normal]current Competition 
[normal]Commission investigation into the private motor insurance market
[normal] has 
[normal]provisionally 
[normal]conclu
[normal]ded
[normal] 
[normal]that “
[normal]the separation of cost liability and cost control in the provision of post-accident services to non-fault 
[normal]PMI (personal motor insurance) c
[normal]laimants does appear to give rise to a moral hazard problem, whereby the ultimate costs paid by the fault insurer are 
[normal]higher than they would otherwise be
[normal].”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The investigation has found that 
[normal]this 
[normal]can increase the average cost of a non-fault repair by 
[normal]‘
[normal]up to around £270 if the non-fault insurer manages the repair
[normal]’
[normal].
[normal] However, while these inflated costs are passed on to the motorist in higher prem
[normal]iums, the insurance companies have been
[normal] banking the referral fees to boost their bottom line. Direct Line, for example, benefited to the tune of £25.9m in 2012 from revenue fo
[normal]r vehicle recovery and repair services
[normal], according to its annual report. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Legal referral fees go in-house[bold] - 
[normal]Admiral 
[normal]has responded to the ban on personal injury referral fees, from which it earned £18.6m in 2012, by setting 
[normal]up its own legal businesses, 
[normal]Admi
[normal]ral Law and BDE Law. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Admiral says ‘n
[normal]ew and proposed reforms to the handling of bodily injury claims mean that the businesses are not expected to make a material contribution to Group profits in the foreseeable future
[normal]’
[normal].
[normal] However, Admiral is clearly trying t
[normal]o gain a competitive advantage following the 
[normal]Jackson
[normal] reforms by creating a legal business that has a guaranteed income
[normal] and no marketing costs for 
[normal]cases that are, in effect, referred in-house
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Online driving records[bold] 
[normal]–Cabinet Office Minister
[normal] Francis Maude
[normal] 
[normal]told the media this month
[normal] (9.1.14) that most of the UK’s 40 million motorists would see premiums fall as a result of the introduction of online driving records by the middle of next year.  The Association of British Insurers said ‘honest’ motorists could s
[normal]ee premiums fall by up to £15 a year. But no one produced a shred of evidence to support these assertions
[normal], and there is every reason to assume – based on the financial behaviour of the car insurers outlined above – that 
[normal]any
[normal] cost saving to the insurers from accessing online driving records will simply boost 
[normal]their 
[normal]profits
[normal]. This 
[normal]is
[normal] yet another case of the car insurers wanting it both ways: taxpayers funding systems that help them make more profit for distribution to shareholder
[normal]s
[normal]. 
[normal]Car insurers should be charged for accessing online driving records with the proceeds earmarked for road safety[bold] (see below).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
