[normal]4[bold] Transparency and political lobbying[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The facts outlined above add up to a market that serves consumers poorly, to say the l
[normal]east. We believe this situation has come about because the car insurers have gained a disproportionate influence over government policy and 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]lack 
[normal]of 
[normal]a
[normal] regulatory framework 
[normal]means 
[normal]that 
[normal]there is insufficient 
[normal]transparency and accountability.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1 Lobbying  [bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The car insurers are brazen
[normal] 
[normal]about their lobbying activities. Direct Line, for example, said in its annual report:  
[normal]“
[normal]With the ongoing debates in the motor market surrounding referral and legal fees, the increase in whiplash claims and the implementation 
[normal]of the gender directive, we aim to be leaders through this period of change and lobby for reform to provide the best outcome for our customers and shareholders
[normal]”
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Being ‘leaders’ appears to mean 
[normal]a regular flow of 
[normal]e mails 
[normal]to MPs from individual insurance companies and from the ABI and the holding of meetings on parliamentary premises 
[normal]about a ‘whiplash pandemic’ 
[normal]and a ‘compensation culture’ 
[normal]without 
[normal]no apparent embarrassment
[normal] at the inconsistency - to put it euphemistically 
[normal]–
[normal] 
[normal]that they are at the same time saying in
[normal] their shareholder communications 
[normal]that 
[normal]bodily injury claims have been falling in recent years. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is 
[normal]a 
[normal]lobbying activity 
[normal]that 
[normal]would not be covered by the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-Party Campaigning and Trade Un
[normal]ion Administration Bill in its present form.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2 [bold]Transparency [bold]and accountability[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Car insurance is a necessity
[normal] yet, unlike other necessities such as utilities, it is not regulated in a way that ensures the public and policy makers have the 
[normal]facts
[normal] they need to make informed decisions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]evidence
[normal] in this submission has been painstakingly 
[normal]extracted 
[normal]from various published 
[normal]sources but 
[normal]it is
[normal] far from complete because the car insurers are not required to provide information about their finances and c
[normal]laims in a consistent and comprehensive way
[normal]. In our view
[normal],
[normal] a
[normal]ny company
[normal] selling insurance to UK motorists -
[normal] whether private or public,
[normal] foreign or UK owned - should be obliged to conform to the same reporting sta
[normal]ndards. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the short term, the S[bold]elect Committee [bold]may wish to [bold]ask[bold] AVIVA [bold]and AXA why they are not meeting international accountancy standards for public companies by reporting separately [bold]on the UK car insurance market.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5 Road safety[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Louise 
[normal]Ellman’s
[normal] letter raises the important question of
[normal] information sharing 
[normal]between the Department for Transport and police 
[normal]about accidents so that spending on road safety can be better targeted. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK has 77 cars per kilometre of road compared to a European average of 43. 
[normal]Congestion is bound to increase th
[normal]e risk of road accidents and therefore personal injury. Car insurers are in possession of vital data that could be used to highlight acciden
[normal]t trouble-
[normal]spots and prioritise 
[normal]the allocation of funds for 
[normal]investment in road
[normal] safety. 
[normal]In our view[bold],[bold] it is without que[bold]stion that t[bold]hey should therefore be [bold]required to take part in[bold] any information-sharing arrangements.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]At the same time, there is a strong case for levying a windfall tax on car insurers so that some of the profits bonanza they have enjoyed in recent years is[bold] channelled into investment in road safety. The money raised could be ring-fenced and used to tackle the worst trouble-spots as a matter of urgency.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6 Access to justice[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Raising the small claims track limit[bold] - 
[normal]The car insurers are actively lobbying for the small claims track limit to be raised to £5,000 from the current level of £1,000.  
[normal]Our arguments against the raising of the small claims limit can be summarised as:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]At the very least
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]we fully support the view expressed in L
[normal]ouise 
[normal]Ellman’s
[normal] letter that the g
[normal]overnment shou
[normal]ld analyse the impact of the electronic portal 
[normal]before
[normal] it considers whether or not to increase th
[normal]e threshold.
[normal] 
[normal]It is clear from [bold]our evidence [bold]above that [bold]the number of bodily injury clai[bold]ms is not as high as was claimed by the car insurers[bold] and therefore there i[bold]s no case for rushing into further legal changes until the facts and all the implications are much clearer.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]From our own work, we know that people with genuine claims are often pressurised into accepting less compensation than they deserve by 
[normal]insurers and 
[normal]lawyers acting for
[normal] them
[normal]. We attach as an appendix 
[normal]the 
[normal]case of
[normal] Donald and Enid 
[normal]Winterbottom
[normal], which highlights how raising the threshold for the portal could undermine access to justice for genuine claimants.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Information for motorists on their [bold]legal rights[bold] – The Competition Commission’s recommendation that motorists should automatically be provided with information on their legal rights in the event of an accident is very welcome (Private Motor Insurance Market Investigation – Notice of Possible
[normal] Remedies, 17.12.13). We are, however, concerned that the Commission suggests in 21(c) that this should be provided by the Association of British Insurers. In our view, this would be a travesty. The ABI exists to protect the interests of car insurers, wher
[normal]eas any statement of consumer rights must be seen to be entirely independen
[normal]t.
[normal] 
