[normal]Appendix A[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Case study: Donald and Enid [bold]Winterbottom[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Donald and Enid 
[normal]Winterbottom
[normal], aged 81 and 79 respectively, w
[normal]ere injured on 12 January 2012 when a car overtaking from the opposite direction hit their car head-on. 
[normal]Mrs
[normal] 
[normal]Winterbottom
[normal] was airlifted to hospital with a severe whiplash injury. The next day while 
[normal]Enid
[normal] was still in hospital, and with no discussion with her
[normal], their legal expense insurers, 
[normal]Cogents
[normal], started a claim. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The medical ‘expert’ appointed by 
[normal]Cogents
[normal] estimated that both Donald and Enid would recover from their injuries within 
[normal]seven
[normal] months and the company estimated damages for 
[normal]Mrs
[normal] 
[normal]Winterbottom
[normal] at £1,800
[normal] – £2,000.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Donald and Enid rejected the offer and moved their claim to 
[normal]Mr
[normal] 
[normal]Winterbottom’s
[normal] old union, Unite Legal Services, in November 2012. In July 2013 Thompsons Solicitors settled 
[normal]Mrs
[normal] 
[normal]Winterbottom’s
[normal] case for £8,000, four times the estimated damages. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The lawyer at Thompsons who ran the case, Hazel Webb, found that 
[normal]Cogents
[normal] had failed to take proper instructions from the 
[normal]Winterbottoms
[normal] and referred them to the wrong type of medical expert who missed the long-term impact of one of 
[normal]Mrs
[normal] 
[normal]Winterbottom’s
[normal] injuri
[normal]es – namely, numbness in her hand which needed an 
[normal]orthopaedic
[normal] specialist to whom Thompsons referred her.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Enid 
[normal]Winterbottom
[normal] said
[normal]:
[normal] 
[normal]“We didn’t ask for Cogent and we can only assume they got our details from our car insurance company. We were in shock after t
[normal]he accident yet we were harassed with phone calls from 
[normal]Cogents
[normal] pushing us to make a claim and then, when we agreed, the way we were dealt with was so impersonal we felt like we were just a statistic
[normal].
[normal] Their letters were in legal mumbo jumbo
[normal],
[normal] and we struggle
[normal]d to make sense of t
[normal]hem
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
